                    h2 HIGHLIGHTS
                    .sep.taller
                    p There are three topics worth highlighting during the course of designing filters.
                    h3 1. Batch Filters vs. Interactive Filters
                    p While filters may look similar in many products, their behaviors vary widely. Can users adjust multiple filters before the results of the compound query are returned, or are the results returned after each filter value is specified? Answers to the question indicate two different filtering mechanism: batch filters and interactive filters. Choosing between a batch and an interactive filter implementation will depend on user intent and site speed. 
                    p Exploratory users who do not have a clear search goal still need to learn about the structure of the search space and the possible options. These users will benefit most from interactive filtering. Alternatively, determined users who already have multiple criteria in mind will benefit from batch filtering. However, it is difficult to accurately predict users’ mindset while they are filtering. In this case, one solution is letting users tell you when they’re done selecting filters. This essentially means to include an apply button in the filter design. Users can click on that button once they’ve indicated all the filter values that they are interested in. This method gives flexibility to both exploratory and determined users.
                    p Site speed is a much more obvious factor. If you expect the queries to be instantaneous then interactive filtering will be less offensive. If however your product is likely to be slow, then the batch filtering can save users some wait time.
                    p To conclude, knowing when to stop and apply filters is key to allowing users smoothly progress towards their goals while maintaining a sense of UI stability and user mastery.
                    h3 2. Powerful Equals Optimal?
                    p Usually powerful features increase users’ capability and flexibility. However, this rule does not apply everywhere. A more powerful filtering feature does not necessarily guarantee an optimal user experience. 
                    p The first example is about dynamic filtering mechanism, which is popular among e-commerce giants, e.g. Taobao, and JD.com. The reasons why they stick to this pattern are because 1) they have countless commodities; 2) commodities are mainly physical; 3) servers are robust and reliable. Compared with them, 1) Booking.com has relatively small inventory in domestic market; 2) commodities are heavily influenced by seasons; 3) servers are remote and slow. In this case, if I apply the same solution, users are more likely to see drastic page refreshes or filter shifts, which severely disrupt their filtering process.
                    p Another example is about separating the location filters. Due to the immaturity of current geographical information and the misplacement of map feature, I proposed to postpone this separation.
                    p To summarize, the design for filters was heavily influenced by
